116. Proof: In $\triangle B_{1} B_{2} B_{3}$, let
$$\begin{aligned}
\lambda_{1} & =-\sin B_{1}+\sin B_{2}+\sin B_{3} \\
\lambda_{2} & =\sin B_{1}-\sin B_{2}+\sin B_{3} \\
\lambda_{3} & =\sin B_{1}+\sin B_{2}-\sin B_{3}
\end{aligned}$$

By using the sum-to-product identities, we get
$$\begin{array}{l}
\lambda_{1}=4 \sin \frac{B_{2}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{3}}{2} \cos \frac{B_{1}}{2} \\
\lambda_{2}=4 \sin \frac{B_{3}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{1}}{2} \cos \frac{B_{2}}{2} \\
\lambda_{3}=4 \sin \frac{B_{1}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{2}}{2} \cos \frac{B_{3}}{2}
\end{array}$$

Thus, we have
$$\begin{array}{c}
\text { Left side of the original equation }=\frac{\sin \frac{B_{2}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{3}}{2}+\sin \frac{B_{3}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{1}}{2}+\sin \frac{B_{1}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{2}}{2}}{\sqrt{\sin \frac{B_{1}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{2}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{3}}{2}}} \\
\text { Right side of the original equation }=(6-3 \sqrt{3}) \sqrt{\sin \frac{B_{1}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{2}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{3}}{2}}+\frac{\cos \frac{B_{1}}{2} \cos \frac{B_{2}}{2} \cos \frac{B_{3}}{2}}{\sqrt{\sin \frac{B_{1}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{2}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{3}}{2}}}
\end{array}$$

According to the trigonometric identities
$$\begin{array}{l}
\sin \frac{B_{1}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{2}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{3}}{2}=\frac{r}{4 R} \\
\cos \frac{B_{1}}{2} \cos \frac{B_{2}}{2} \cos \frac{B_{3}}{2}=\frac{s}{4 R}
\end{array}$$

where $R, r, s$ are the circumradius, inradius, and semiperimeter of $\triangle B_{1} B_{2} B_{3}$, respectively. Substituting these into the above equations, we get
$$\sin \frac{B_{2}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{3}}{2}+\sin \frac{B_{3}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{1}}{2}+\sin \frac{B_{1}}{2} \sin \frac{B_{2}}{2} \geqslant \frac{(6-3 \sqrt{3}) r}{4 R}+\frac{s}{4 R}$$

This inequality holds, as can be seen in the book "Inequality Research" (edited by Yang Xuezhi, published by Tibet People's Publishing House in June 2000), in the article "A Review of the Research on Inequalities of Half-Angle Trigonometric Functions in Triangles" by Yang Xuezhi and Yin Huayan. Therefore, the original equation holds. The original equation also holds for degenerate triangles (one side is zero, the other two sides are equal or the sum of the other two sides equals the third side).

